Simple Linear Regression

# Fit regression model:
score_model <- lm(score ~ bty_avg, data = evals_ch6)
# Get regression table:
get_regression_table(score_model)

Let’s calculate the sum of squared residuals using a pipeline:

regression_points %>%
  mutate(squared_residuals = residual^2) %>%
  summarize(sum_of_squared_residuals = sum(squared_residuals))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   sum_of_squared_residuals
##                      <dbl>
## 1                     132.
ggplot(regression_points, mapping=aes(x=residual)) + geom_histogram(bins = 20, color = "white")

Learning Check 544.5.2

Repeat the above steps with the handwriting data from discussion section:

  1. Create a linear model (using the lm() function) to model non-dominant time as the outcome variable and dominant time as the explanatory one.
handwriting.model <- lm(non_dominant ~ dominant, data = handwriting.data)
  1. Use get_regression_table() to get the coefficients for the regression model.
get_regression_table(handwriting.model)
## # A tibble: 2 x 7
##   term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept    6.29      0.845      7.44       0    4.60      7.97
## 2 dominant     0.973     0.124      7.87       0    0.726     1.22
  1. What would the expected value of non-dominant time be for a name that took 6 seconds to write with one’s dominant hand?

estimate = 6.286s + (0.973dominant) = 6.286s + 0.9736s = 12.124 seconds

  1. Use get_regression_summaries() to get information about how “good” the model is. Comment on how much variance is explained by the model. What’s the average deviation from the predicted value?
get_regression_summaries(handwriting.model)
## # A tibble: 1 x 8
##   r_squared adj_r_squared   mse  rmse sigma statistic p_value    df
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.466         0.458  11.5  3.39  3.44      61.9       0     2

r squared is the statistic that explains how much variance is explained by the model. In this case, it explains around 46.6% of the variance, which isn’t too great (but isn’t too bad either). The average deviation from the predicted value is quantified by the root mean square error, which in this case is about 3.4s, which means on average the real values are 3.4 seconds away from the values our model predicts.

  1. Identify the two most extreme residual values. What do those values mean? Can you infer anything about the individuals with those values?
get_regression_points(handwriting.model) %>% arrange(residual)
## # A tibble: 73 x 5

The two points with the largest residuals are 26.73s non-dom vs. 10.93s dom (who took a particularly long time to write with their non-dominant hand given what our model would have predicted given their dominant writing time), and 21.23 non-dom vs. 23.55 dom (who took a particularly short time to write with their non-dominant hand given what our model would have predicted given their dominant writing time).

One categorical predictor variable

Let’s return to the Gapminder data:

library(gapminder)
gapminder2007 <- gapminder %>%
  filter(year == 2007) %>%
  select(country, lifeExp, continent, gdpPercap)

It loaded the gapminder dataset, then picked out a subset of the data that only contains the data for 2007 and contained in the columns country, lifeExp (life expentancy), continent, and gdpPercap (gross domestic product per capita).

The output tells me that there are 142 countries total in this data grouped into five continents. It also tells me that among all of these countries, the mean life expectancy is about 67 years, the median life expentancy is around 72 years, and the total range is between 39.6 and 82.6. The fact that the mean is about 5 years lower than the median tells me that there are either outliers or a long tail on the low side (negative skew), which is confirmed by the little histogram.

ggplot(gapminder2007, aes(x = lifeExp)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, color = "white") +
  labs(x = "Life expectancy", y = "Number of countries",

Learning Check 544.5.5

Add a column called “deltaAfrica” to the lifeExp_by_continent dataframe that is calculated as the difference of each mean value from the mean value for Africa. Round your values to 1 decimal point. For example, the value for “Americas” should be 18.8.

lifeExp_by_continent <- lifeExp_by_continent %>% mutate(deltaAfrica = round(mean - 54.806, digits = 1))

Learning Check 544.5.6

How do the values of “estimate” compare to “deltaAfrica” from the earlier Learning Check?

The values of estimate reflect the same thing as the values of deltaAfrica, namely the difference of that continent’s mean from Africa’s mean, except for the first row. The values of estimate, then, are: Africa’s mean, then how much the mean of each other continent differs from Africa’s. Difference of means must be the method the linear model uses to make its estimates when dealing with categorical predictor variables.

get_regression_summaries(lifeExp_model)
## # A tibble: 1 x 8
##   r_squared adj_r_squared   mse  rmse sigma statistic p_value    df
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.635         0.625  52.8  7.26  7.40      59.7       0     5

Learning Check 544.5.7

How “good” is this model?

Well, the r squared value of 63.5% explanation of the variance seems pretty good. However, having estimations an average of 7.26 years off the actual values seems a bit high. Perhaps this means that there are some outliers in the data, countries who have a life expentancy that is much higher or lower than the rest of their continent.
